<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="96" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,639,194,1729]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,298,1257,1278]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is restricted to a number of geographically close islands in the Bahia de Los Angeles, Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[397,492,1310,1331]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">California</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[508,626,1309,1331]" captionStart-0="Fig" captionStart-1="Fig" captionStartId-0="5.[175,207,1686,1705]" captionStartId-1="6.[197,229,1443,1462]" captionTargetBox-0="[177,1146,842,1663]" captionTargetBox-1="[173,1193,194,1420]" captionTargetId-0="figure-59@5.[177,1147,841,1663]" captionTargetId-1="figure-146@6.[172,1194,194,1420]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionText-0="Fig. 13. Craniotus species, distribution map. Blue pentagrams = C. mardecortesi. Green circles = C. triplehorni. Red triangles = C. pubescens." captionText-1="Fig. 14. Craniotus species, distribution around Bahia de los Angeles. Red square = C. pubescens. Green circles = C. mardecortesi." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4911735" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4911737" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/4911735/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/4911737/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Figs. 13–14</figureCitation>
). It is also found on the mainland on an isolated elevated promontory, directly south of these islands. This unnamed area, with capes Punta Rosa and Punta Que Malo, was likely insular until recent times (
<figureCitation box="[221,298,1443,1464]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[197,229,1443,1462]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,194,1420]" captionTargetId="figure-146@6.[172,1194,194,1420]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 14. Craniotus species, distribution around Bahia de los Angeles. Red square = C. pubescens. Green circles = C. mardecortesi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4911737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4911737/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[320,530,1442,1463]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Craniotus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubescens">
<emphasis box="[320,530,1442,1463]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Craniotus pubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, found on the rest of the mainland around Bahia de Los Angeles, is not found on either the islands or the adjacent promontory.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="96" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,639,194,1729]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,280,1549,1570]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[294,501,1548,1569]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Craniotus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triplehorni">
<emphasis box="[294,501,1548,1569]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Craniotus triplehorni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily separated from other 
<taxonomicName box="[357,527,1575,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" genus="Craniotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[357,452,1575,1596]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Craniotus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the less globose pronotum with lateral margins bearing only a few (4) lateral connate projections and the fine, unevenly scattered elytral punctures.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="96" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,639,194,1729]" lastBlockId="3.[685,1172,194,242]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[175,290,1682,1703]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for Charles (Chuck) Triplehorn, a prominent worker in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[685,826,194,215]" class="Insecta" family="Tenebrionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Tenebrionidae</taxonomicName>
and a great mentor to many students of systematic entomology.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
